1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,039
Track 1 doesn't score you on what your
agent can do. It scores you on how few

2
00:00:05,119 --> 00:00:10,551
tokens it needs to do it — while staying
accurate. Most teams will point every task

3
00:00:10,631 --> 00:00:14,580
at the biggest model and call it done.
That's the expensive way.

4
00:00:14,660 --> 00:00:20,688
Our routing agent asks one question before
it ever calls an LLM: does this task

5
00:00:20,768 --> 00:00:26,567
actually need one? A regex-and-AST
classifier catches arithmetic, date math,

6
00:00:26,647 --> 00:00:31,988
string ops, unit conversion, and
extraction — and solves them for zero

7
00:00:32,068 --> 00:00:37,867
tokens. Everything else goes to the
cheapest model that can handle it, gated

8
00:00:37,947 --> 00:00:43,898
by a confidence check. Only tasks that
fail that gate escalate — once — to the

9
00:00:43,978 --> 00:00:48,000
strongest model. No retries loop, no
self-verification tax.

10
00:00:48,080 --> 00:00:54,820
Watch the route field. 'What is 847 times
36' — that's real arithmetic, correctly

11
00:00:54,900 --> 00:01:01,557
answered, zero Fireworks tokens spent. No
model was called. In our 200-task eval

12
00:01:01,637 --> 00:01:06,556
set, 65 tasks — just under a third —
resolve exactly this way.

13
00:01:06,636 --> 00:01:11,745
This one needs a model — it's sentiment
classification. The router picks the

14
00:01:11,825 --> 00:01:17,136
cheapest model that's adequate for the
job, gpt-oss-20b, with a minimal prompt,

15
00:01:17,216 --> 00:01:22,527
temperature zero, and reasoning suppressed
so it doesn't burn completion tokens

16
00:01:22,607 --> 00:01:27,851
thinking out loud. Notice the token count
— small, and it's what actually gets

17
00:01:27,931 --> 00:01:29,144
billed, not an estimate.

18
00:01:29,224 --> 00:01:36,138
Every call — Tier 0 or Tier 1 — updates a
running ledger: raw tokens, price-weighted

19
00:01:36,218 --> 00:01:43,049
cost, and route distribution. That's the
same ledger the eval harness uses to score

20
00:01:43,129 --> 00:01:44,700
the full 200-task run.

21
00:01:44,780 --> 00:01:51,716
Across the full 200-task eval set: 99.5%
accuracy — 199 out of 200 correct.

22
00:01:51,796 --> 00:01:59,288
Thirty-two and a half percent of tasks
never touch a model at all. And against an

23
00:01:59,368 --> 00:02:06,582
honest baseline — same tasks, strongest
model, no routing tricks — total token

24
00:02:06,662 --> 00:02:13,598
spend drops by roughly 47 to 51%. The
whole run costs a third of a cent and

25
00:02:13,678 --> 00:02:15,960
finishes in under 24 seconds.

26
00:02:16,040 --> 00:02:21,245
One more thing: the model registry
auto-prefers Gemma at equal price tier

27
00:02:21,325 --> 00:02:27,099
whenever the harness allows it — that's
unit-tested and ready today. On July 7th,

28
00:02:27,179 --> 00:02:32,954
when we probed the live Fireworks account,
Gemma wasn't exposed on serverless, so

29
00:02:33,034 --> 00:02:38,595
this run routes through gpt-oss and
DeepSeek instead. The preference activates

30
00:02:38,675 --> 00:02:44,450
automatically the moment Gemma becomes
available — no code change needed. Routing

31
00:02:44,530 --> 00:02:47,900
intelligence, not raw compute. That's the
whole pitch.

